k stops with me and I'm big enough to take it,\" said Sutton, who had harsh words for the men's endurance team, who managed only eighth in qualifying in the team pursuit, a key benchmark for Great Britain and a discipline in which they had won a medal every year since 2000, apart from a fourth place in 2009. Coming as it did on day one, that result set the tone for a week in which only Ed Clancy's fifth place in the omnium - with three first places in the six counting events - offering any relief from the gloom.</p><p>\"They need to look at themselves,\" said Sutton, pointedly. \"They got it wrong. They went out for the festive season, came back and weren't where they should have been (performance-wise). I've got concerns with the current crop of riders we've got and it's only them that can change. We've just gone backwards and I think the accountability rests with the riders.\" It was a result that raised eyebrows, among onlookers such as Dan Hunt, the coach who guided Clancy, Steven Burke, Peter Kennaugh and Geraint Thomas to gold in London, who told the Guardian afterwards, \"What concerns me is the quality of the teams in front of them. Being beaten by Germany, Switzerland and Spain is worrying.\"</p><p>It had been suggested the younger riders in the endurance squad, 21-year-old Sam Harrison, and 20-year-olds Owain Doull and Jon Dibben could eventually rival double Olympic team pursuit gold winners Clancy and Thomas, but Sutton is not so sure. \"Ed's special. I don't think the other boys have got the talent if I was totally honest,\" Sutton added.</p><p>\"When you've got a man like [London gold medallist] Steven Burke not to make the squad, he needs to reflect on where's he going. This isn't just pointing the finger at the men's team pursuit. This is not me criticising my team. I'm here to support them. [But] it's the World Championships and they have come here to perform. If they leave one stone unturned they're going to get exposed.\"</p><p>Sutton added that he would like the four-time Olympic champion Sir Bradley Wiggins and the London 2012 gold medallist Peter Kennaugh to state their intentions over returning to the track for Rio. \"I know Pete's appetite for the track is still very big,\" Sutton said. \"We would welcome him with open arms, and Bradley. If Brad's definitely going to ride the track I think if he was to say sooner rather than later that is definitely a goal then that might just be that little bit of upward pressure that the other guys need.\"</p><p>Brailsford had said that he would reassess his role with the squad as part of the review process after Cali and Boardman - part of the senior management team that guided the squad to seven gold medals in Beijing – said that Brailsford needed to choose between Sky and Great Britain. \"[the team] needs a boss,\" Boardman said. \"I believe Dave's making a decision on what he's going to do, but it needs a full-time boss. Dave would clearly be the best full-time boss, but if he's not going to do that, it might be better if somebody else comes in and takes the reins.</p><p>\"He's such a character, if he's still there it's difficult for people to go in and take command, but it needs somebody like him. Shane [Sutton, the head coach] is great, a good second in command, but perhaps not the person to be the big boss. The potential is all still there. It just might need somebody to pull it all together. They're just missing an edge. If you were concerned about anything, it's the fact they're finding it difficult to pinpoint and haven't seen it coming into the event.\"</p><p>Sutton was keen to defend his boss, with whom he has worked closely since the Athens Games. \"For people to start pointing the finger at Dave is unfounded. This guy's been the greatest leader in British sport history. His legacy will go on and on.\" Sutton was adamant both he and Brailsford have the enthusiasm and desire to revitalise the British track team. \"We love a battle. We've got a real scrap on here now. I don't want to go anywhere; I probably want it more than the riders. I want to stay here, I want to take them into Rio (in 2016) and into Tokyo (in 2020), if I've got the opportunity.\"</p>","headline":"Shane Sutton slates Team GB's poor performance at world championships","trailText":"<p>Shane Sutton, the British Cycling head coach, was uncompromising in his criticism of an underperforming Team GB at the world championships</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/3/1393863423833/Shane-Sutton-the-British--006.jpg","wordcount":"891","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-06T23:01:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/03/shane-sutton-team-gb-world-track-championships","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/mar/03/shane-sutton-team-gb-world-track-championships","tags":[{"id":"sport/team-gb","webTitle":"Team GB","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/team-gb","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/team-gb","references":[]},{"id":"sport/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/cycling","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/team-sky","webTitle":"Team Sky","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/team-sky","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/team-sky","references":[]},{"id":"sport/dave-brailsford","webTitle":"Dave Brailsford","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/dave-brailsford","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/dave-brailsford","references":[]},{"id":"sport/sport","webTitle":"Sport","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/spor