 | William Fotheringham","webPublicationDate":"2014-03-03T17:48:00Z","sectionName":"Sport","sectionId":"sport","id":"sport/blog/2014/mar/03/six-lessons-great-britain-cycling-world-track-championships","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3n87k","standfirst":"The British squad underperformed in Colombia, and the signs are there that the rest of the world is catching up fast<br />•<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/gallery/2014/mar/03/chrishoy-laura-trott\" title=\"\"> Behind the scenes at the world championships – in pictures</a>","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<h2>Another wake-up call for Great Britain, and a loud one</h2><p></p><p>This is the second major championships in a row – following last year's world road event – where Great Britain have been unable to live up to the high standards they began setting midway through the Beijing Olympiad. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/02/jason-kenny-british-cyclists-cycling-world-championships\" title=\"\">With no medals won by the men – sprinters or endurance riders</a> –for the first time since lottery funding began in 1998, that means half the programme was off the pace, two years out from the next Olympics. On the plus side, the women's endurance riders continue to perform – although Canada pushed the team pursuit quartet harder than ever –while the sprinters are clearly in the mix.</p><p></p><h2>GB's generation gap</h2><p></p><p>In hindsight, London looks like the beginning of a rebuilding process after the departure of the golden Beijing generation led by Chris Hoy, Victoria Pendleton and Bradley Wiggins. The process is proving more contorted than might have been expected. Some riders who might have figured in the men's endurance programme up to now have options on the road with Team Sky and other squads, while others such as Mark Cavendish and Wiggins are talking about returning for Rio. In Hoy, GB have lost a charismatic leader and powerhouse who is not easily replaced; Pendleton's successors, Jess Varnish and Becky James, are heading in the right direction, but are not yet the finished article.</p><p></p><h2>The rest of the world is progressing fast</h2><p></p><p>The worry for the British is that other nations are clearly on the move. The French and Germans finished joint top of the medal table, with François Pervis and Kristina Vogel the dominant performers – and these established nations look to be gaining more strength in depth, as do Australia – but there is clear progress being made in less obvious quarters: New Zealand continue to make strides, the Chinese women's sprinters are improving; Colombia have found new stars in Edwin Ávila, winner of the points race, and the keirin silver medallist, Fabián Puerta, and the Irish have potential in Ryan Mullen.</p><p></p><h2>The men's endurance squad needs an urgent rethink</h2><p></p><p>This was their worst world championships since the start of lottery funding, with the team beaten by Spain, Germany and Switzerland inter alia en route to eighth place in the team pursuit qualifying round, followed by low placings in the bunch races, with Ed Clancy's respectable display in the omnium the only consolation. If Ireland, without an indoor track or any serious funding, can turn out a decent bunch racer in Martyn Irvine and in Mullen a sparkling young pursuiter, the British need to take a long look at themselves and their collective approach. Are they racing enough? Is the throughput of riders from the academy as good as it was, and are the under-23s being pushed as hard as they were when its former head Rod Ellingworth produced such talents as Cavendish and Clancy?</p><p></p><h2>Dave Brailsford needs to clarify his role</h2><p></p><p>Brailsford, the man at the head of the programme – although he has delegated the day to day running of it to Shane Sutton – has been publicly stating that he needs to clarify his role, and that he feels overstretched by his joint commitments to Team Sky and GB. That cannot fail to have an impact all the way down the chain of command and right through to the riders, who are entitled to wonder what is going on at the top. It's clear that Brailsford has to decide what he is going to do – but it is not that simple. The problem he has now is that if he reduces his role at GB, it looks as if he is walking away just as the ship is hitting choppy waters.</p><p></p><h2>The UCI needs to get behind this sport</h2><p></p><p>The racing from Colombia was vibrant, most notably Ávila's victory in the points race, but track cycling is struggling at international level where it is being inadequately marketed. This season the UCI struggled to put on three rounds of the World Cup, with two going to Mexico, one in a velodrome criticised as substandard. France and Germany are producing a wealth of top riders, particularly sprinters, but it is years since either of these major nations hosted a World Cup or world championships. The sport's governing body needs to ask itself why – <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/03/world-track-cycling-championships-venue-2015-uci\" title=\"\">another item for Brian Cookson's in-tray</a> once he has turned round women's cycling and dealt with the fallout from the Lance Armstrong scandal.</p>","headline":"Six lessons for Great Britain following the world track championships","trailText":"<strong>William Fotheringham:</strong> The British squad underperformed in Colombia, and the signs are there that the rest of the world is catching up fast","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/pictures/2014/3/3/1393851946168/Jason-Kenny-left-and-Grea-006.jpg","wordcount":"738","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-10T13:17:26Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2014/mar/03/six-lessons-great-britain-cycling-world-track-championships","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/blog/2014/mar/03/six-lessons-great-britain-cycling-world-track-championships","tags":[{"i