n the period before the emergence of Victoria Pendleton when the women's side of the squad was relatively weak – taking not a single world championship medal between 2001 and 2004 – while the men were consistent medallists as stars such as Chris Hoy and Bradley Wiggins earned their spurs.</p><p>Jason Kenny, the double Olympic champion in London in 2012 and a gold and silver medallist in Beijing, ended his world championship campaign without a medal for the first time since he made his debut at this level in 2008, but with three fifth places in the keirin, the title he won 12 months ago in Minsk, the match sprint – where he won the minor final on Saturday evening – and the team sprint, where he, Philip Hindes and Kian Emadi repeated their placing of last year.</p><p>\"It's fractions,\" Kenny said. \"Unfortunately we're at the wrong end of those fractions. We want to be fractions in front instead of fractions behind. The three fifth [places] tend to speak for themselves. I feel a little bit behind the top runners.\" The problem is that those fractions matter immensely in sprint qualifying, where the evidence suggests that the rest of the world has moved forward since the last Olympic cycling while the Britons have not progressed in comparison.</p><p>As he has done in the past, Kenny started off on the wrong foot by qualifying well down the order, 14th out of 24, guaranteeing that he would meet one of the fastest men later in the tournament; he eventually went out to the most rapid qualifier, François Pervis of France. This was actually a worse qualifying performance than he managed in 2013 in Minsk, when he ran in seventh but again went out in the quarter-finals.</p><p>The other senior member of the British squad, the endurance specialist Ed Clancy, was asked if he had an explanation for the poor form shown by Great Britain's men, and replied. \"No, in a word. This whole track campaign hasn't been a bad one. We've had some great results, great performances, just not this week. Truth be told, this whole week's been a bit of a nightmare. Team pursuit, it started off there.\" The British quartet's eighth place in the event, which probably means most to them, set the tone for the week.</p><p>On Saturday night Clancy finished fifth in the omnium, the event in which he took bronze in London, but his showing in the flying lap, the scratch and kilometre, all of which he won, should have given him the foundation for a medal at least. The points and elimination races are old achilles heels which he has countered in the past with a strong ride in the pursuit; in Cali his pursuit form deserted him. \"With the form I had, fifth is the best I could've hoped for. [The] points and scratch and elimination race weren't that bad. The pursuit I was going nowhere. Back to the drawing board and we'll try to sort it out next year.\"</p><p>The British women, on the other hand,  can move forwards with some confidence. James was unable to retain her title in the keirin but secured bronze after fighting her way back in through the repechage, having been relegated following victory in her first heat for leaving the sprinters' lane. She was well beaten in a final won by Germany's Kristina Vogel, with Australia's Anna Meares second. \"I'm really happy,\" said James. \"It's always disappointing not to win but Kristina Vogel has been flying all season. She deserved it.</p><p>\"I was going out to win it. I should have tried to beat her to the jump but she went over on Anna and Anna had a nice little slipstream while I was just hanging on the outside.</p><p>\"I really enjoyed it. It's a nice way to finish.\"</p><p>Trott was second to Sarah Hammer having faced an uphill task to get past the American from her overnight second place, but could at least point to a stronger than usual showing in the discipline that has lost her ground in the past, the points race, where she ran in fourth.</p><p>There was evidence, too, of the continuing progress of Scotland's Katie Archibald, who was in the hunt in the points race before finishing fourth. She may have been out of the medals but this was only the fourth time she had ridden a points race at international level, and her  improvement could make her one of the stars this summer when the Commonwealth Games take place on her home  ground in Glasgow.</p><p>\"We should rejoice in the fact that our women have done so well here,\" Sutton said. \"It's a credit to them and, being hunted like they're hunted, at every major championships, at every competition, is far tougher than you hunting someone.</p><p>\"They stand up and they're counted every time. I can only admire that and I know that will carry them through in good stead to Rio.</p><p>\"I'm not going to compare one against the other. I'd just like to think the boys will take inspiration from what the girls have done off the back of winning the Olympics and then going on to win another couple of world titles. \"</p>","headline":"Great Britain men leave Cycling World Championships empty-handed","trailText":"The British men left Colombia without a medal but Becky James took bronze in the keirin and Laura Trott scooped a second successive world omnium silver","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/pictures/2014/3/2/1393762238183/Jason-Kenny-003.jpg","wordcount":"992","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-05T12:25:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/02/jason-kenny-british-cyclists-cycling-world-championships","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/mar/02/jason-kenny-british-cyclists-cycling-world-championships","tags":[{"id":"sport/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/cycling","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/jasonkenny","webTitle":"Jason Kenny","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":