14/feb/28/britain-women-team-pursuit-world-track-cycling-gold\" title=\"\">Jo Rowsell, Trott, Katie Archibald and Elinor Barker took gold in the team event</a>, Rowsell's solo performance over the 3,000m was a commanding one: she qualified fastest and exploited her strongest suit, her fast start, to take an early lead in the final against America's Sarah Hammer, the current world record holder who has dominated the discipline with five world titles since 2006.</p><p>Rowsell gained a second early on, and never faltered, which was good going for a rider who later said it had been \"touch and go\" whether she would get on the plane for Colombia after a chest infection. Like most track riders, she suffers from \"pursuiters' cough\" – the hacking cough that happens as the lungs cope with extreme effort in a dry, dusty velodrome– but her latest attack two weeks ago reacted badly with her asthma. \"I wasn't bed-bound, but I couldn't train. I missed three training sessions, which in hindsight perhaps did me good, gave me a bit more rest,\" she said.</p><p>It is the 25-year-old's first solo world title and it will make her the clear favourite for the title in the Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, where the organisers have made a major error in not including a women's team event.</p><p>\"I am so excited for the Commonwealth Games,\" she said. \"I didn't do it last time in Delhi [2010] because I was ill with glandular fever. It's my first chance to train for individual pursuit, because we do all our training based around [the] team.\"</p><p>Rowsell also has her eyes on the road time trial in Glasgow, having won last year's national championship at the discipline on Scottish roads. \"We'll see how that goes nearer the time. If, as it gets closer to the event, I think the pursuit's suffering, I'll prioritise the pursuit. I'd love to compete in both of those, though.\"</p><p>Rowsell has been Britain's undisputed star of the opening phase, but the sprinters have held their end up with a bronze for Becky James and Varnish in the team event; the pair were unlucky to meet in the quarter-final of the match sprint where Varnish deprived James of a chance to retain her title. One of the most positive notes for British hopes in the longer term is that Cali looks to have marked <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/oct/26/jess-varnish-troubled-year-world-cup\" title=\"\">Varnish's definitive return to form after a back injury that put her out for five months last year</a>.</p><p>In contrast to the women, the men have endured a torrid start to the championships, although Ed Clancy has a chance of a medal in the omnium after ending the first day in sixth place with the three events that favour him remaining. There will be another medal chance in the men's match sprint with the Olympic champion, Jason Kenny.</p><p>In the first three days, however, the team sprinters' fifth place fell short of the standard they set for themselves at Olympic Games while the rest of the world, led by the New Zealanders and the Germans, have moved forward since London. The world title that has eluded them since 2005 remains as distant as ever, while Kenny fell foul of the random nature of the keirin in his defence of the title he won last year, being baulked by a crash in the final en route to fifth.</p><p>The biggest worry for the Great Britain team, however, is among the men's endurance events. <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/feb/27/world-track-championships-mens-pursuit-failure\" title=\"\">The team pursuit quartet's eighth place in their qualifying round </a>was their lowest since lottery funding began in 1998, which will give some pause for reflection two years out from Rio.</p><p>In the non-Olympic solo endurance disciplines – the scratch, points and individual pursuit – Britain have been well behind the pace set by other nations including Ireland, who do not have an indoor velodrome to train in and function on a minuscule budget yet have come away with a silver medal for Martyn Irvine in the scratch race and an encouraging fourth for the youngster Ryan Mullen in the pursuit.</p>","headline":"Gold star Jo Rowsell: 'I am so excited for the Commonwealth Games'","trailText":"While Great Britain's men stumbled in the first three days of the world track championships in Cali, Colombia, and have yet to win a medal with only a few chances remaining, the women have been the stars of the show","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/pictures/2014/3/1/1393686424996/Jo-Rowsell-GB-cyclist-at--006.jpg","wordcount":"743","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-04T15:20:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/mar/01/gold-jo-rowsell-commonwealth-games","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/mar/01/gold-jo-rowsell-commonwealth-games","tags":[{"id":"sport/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/cycling","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/commonwealthgames2014","webTitle":"Commonwealth Games 2014","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/commonwealthgames2014","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/commonwealthgames2014","references":[]},{"id":"sport/sport","webTitle":"Sport","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/sport","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/sport","references":[]},{"id":"profile/williamfotheringham","webTitle":"William Fotheringham","rcsId":"GNL069141","r2ContributorId":"16575","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/contributor/2007/09/28/william_fotheringham_140x14.jpg","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>William Fotheringham is the Guardian's cycling columnist</p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/williamfoth