track-cycling-gold-individual-pursuit","fields":{"shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3n68t","standfirst":"<p>Youngster revels in ‘craziest 24 hours’ after also winning team pursuit gold, but Anna Meares has to settle for silver</p>","hasStoryPackage":"true","body":"<p>Australia’s Alex Edmondson has claimed his second gold medal at the world track cycling championships with victory in the men’s individual pursuit.<br></p><p>The 20-year-old narrowly edged out Swiss rider Stefan Kueng in the final in Cali, Colombia, on Friday, beating him by a mere 0.41seconds.<br></p><p>The South Australian had qualified fastest for the event. The win is Edmondson’s second in 24 hours, having taken gold in the team pursuit on Thursday.</p><p>It is also Australia’s fourth consecutive title in the event, after Queensland’s Michael Hepburn claimed back-to-back crowns in 2013 and 2012, and Jack Bobridge took the honours in 2011.<br></p><p>“It’s been the craziest last 24 hours, especially with the team pursuit last night with the boys,” Edmondson said after his race.<br></p><p>“Then to come out here and win another world title, I’ve just got no words.”<br></p><p>Earlier, compatriot Anna Meares narrowly missed out on a record 11th world title, winning silver in the 500m time trial.<br></p><p>The 30-year-old’s time of 33.548secs was not enough to win her pet event, with Germany’s Miriam Welte taking gold in a blistering 33.451secs.<br></p><p>Anastasia Voinova of Russia won bronze.<br></p><p>The South Australian still has two more chances to become the most successful female track cyclist in history this weekend in the sprint and keirin events.<br></p><p>She currently shares the lead on 10 rainbow jerseys with France’s Felicia Ballanger, who claimed five sprint and five time-trial world titles between 1995 and 1999.<br></p><p>Annette Edmondson, Amy Cure, Melissa Hoskins and debutante Bella King added a another medal to Australia’s tally, collecting bronze in the women’s team pursuit.<br></p><p>The quartet beat out Poland in the ride-off for third place.<br></p><p>Australia had won medals in the event in four of the past five championships, including consecutive silvers in 2012 and 2013.</p>","headline":"Alex Edmondson claims world track cycling gold in individual pursuit","trailText":"Youngster revels in ‘craziest 24 hours’ after also winning team pursuit gold, but Anna Meares has to settle for silver","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/28/1393557525063/14a5ea7e-7d1b-491f-9f59-598e7c423d91-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"281","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-03T03:22:44Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/feb/28/alex-edmondson-world-track-cycling-gold-individual-pursuit","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/feb/28/alex-edmondson-world-track-cycling-gold-individual-pursuit","tags":[{"id":"sport/cycling","webTitle":"Cycling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/cycling","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/cycling","references":[]},{"id":"sport/sport","webTitle":"Sport","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/sport","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/sport","references":[]},{"id":"sport/australia-sport","webTitle":"Australia sport","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/australia-sport","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/australia-sport","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/news","webTitle":"News","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/news","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/tone/news","references":[]}],"references":[],"elements":[{"i