men's team pursuit performance in a world championship since the beginning of lottery funding, Dan Hunt, the coach who guided the GB quartet to world and Olympic gold medals and two world records in 2012 has described their ride for eighth place in the title in Cali, Colombia, as \"worrying\", but added there is no immediate need for concern with the Olympic Games in Rio two years away. \"If it was Olympic year they would have a right to panic, but as it is, it will be cause for reflection.\"</p><p>Until Cali, Great Britain had taken team pursuit medals in every world championships since 2000 bar one, the 2009 title series in Pruskov, Poland, where they finished fourth. In both the 1999 and 1998 world championships they finished fifth, making the Cali ride their worst since lottery funding began to transform the squad in 1998. It also compares poorly with their performances at similar points in previous Olympic cycles. In the 2010 world championship in Copenhagen they took silver to Australia by .25sec, in 2006 at Bordeaux they took silver by 0.036sec to Australia, while in 2002, again in Copenhagen, they ended up with bronze after narrowly missing out on the gold-silver ride-off.</p><p>Hunt, who is now the Premier League's head of elite performance, said: \"You need to look at the ride they did in qualifying rather than compare their time with the winners, as having an extra team on the track makes a difference in the final.\" GB qualified eighth, with a time of 4min 04.419sec compared to Denmark's 4:00.176.</p><p>\"What concerns me is the quality of the teams in front of them. Being beaten by Germany, Switzerland and Spain is worrying. Looking at the splits I'd say the wheels came off in the last kilometre, but that's when the effects of altitude kick in.</p><p>\"The one thing they won't do is hit the panic button, but they will clinically reflect on what they've done in the last few months. They'll be disappointed, but they know what improvements to make as the Commonwealth Games and Rio come into view. They've had some bad luck, maybe not had a great winter.\"</p><p>The sense of disappointment for Great Britain was reinforced by the fact that the team pursuit has been regarded for many years as the most prestigious endurance title on the track, reflecting as it does a nation's strength in depth.</p><p>The discipline has largely been a two-horse race in recent years with Great Britain and Australia dominant, with New Zealand, Denmark and Russia the other powerhouses. Cali, however, marked a resurgence for the Danes, thanks partly to the return of Alex Rasmussen after an 18-month ban for missing drugs tests, and to the emergence of the powerful rider Lasse Norman Hansen.</p><p>In Cali, Great Britain fielded only one of the five-man squad that dominated the discipline in 2012. Ed Clancy was the only survivor with his fellow London gold medallist Stephen Burke put out by illness along with Andy Tennant, who was part of the squad that took gold in the Melbourne world championship in 2012, but missed out on a ride in London. The two other London medallists, Geraint Thomas and Peter Kennaugh, are now devoting their attention to road racing full-time.</p><p>\"Behind the scenes we've had some problems,\" admitted Ed Clancy, who also won gold in the Beijing Games in the discipline. \"We knew a week ago we had our backs against the wall. [Andy] Tennant's not here, and he usually goes pretty good. Burkey is a pretty low-profile guy, but when we set our world record in London he was our strongest rider. We have tried a different approach for these track worlds and perhaps it hasn't quite paid off.\"</p><p>With Tennant and Burke out, Clancy was joined by three younger riders, the 21-year old Sam Harrison and two 20-year-olds, Jon Dibben and Owain Doull. However, the world champions in Cali, Australia, also fielded a mix of youth and experience, with three riders under 23 in their five-man squad.</p><p>One problem Great Britain face is t