lsford after the world track championships in Colombia","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<p>Uncertainty is in the humid tropical air in the run-in to the world track championships in Cali, Colombia, where Great Britain completed their pre-event training on the velodrome in spite of rain described as \"biblical\". The downpours left an access tunnel flooded and put the track out of action while the wooden boards dried out, leading to speculation that the championship might be disrupted or, at worst, cancelled, if the weather persists.</p><p>Since the Atlanta Olympic Games in 1996, the last major event to be held on an outdoor velodrome, the UCI has had a policy of running major championships only on indoor tracks to avoid disruption by the weather, but Cali is a compromise: an outdoor track with a temporary roof that is open at the sides. In Tuesday's training session the wind drove the torrential rain under the roof, leaving the track glistening and slippery and temporarily too dangerous to ride on. The championships are due to start on Wednesday.</p><p>Amid pictures of mopping up – scenes that were reminiscent of the recent British floods – the Great Britain sprint head coach, Iain Dyer, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/iaindyer1\" title=\"\">vented his frustration on Twitter</a>. \"Following the MCR [Manchester] World Cup we've not had one venue in two further WCups (both Mexico) &amp; now the World Championships that reach acceptable stds,\" said Dyer, adding, \"Shame the UCI can't stick to its own rules and hold the W Champs indoors.\"</p><p>Dyer had already stated his concerns after the World Cup at Aguascalientes in Mexico in December, which he described to the Guardian afterwards as being \"totally inappropriate as a competition venue\" because of limited access to the track centre, making it hard for paramedics to get to riders who had crashes, and a lack of guardrails at the top of the track.</p><p>Coming as they do midway through the Olympic cycle, the Cali championships should offer the Great Britain staff a chance to assess the work that has to be done before Rio 2016. \"It's a line in the sand, a marker of where we're at against the rest of the world,\" said the performance director, Dave Brailsford. \"And that will then guide us going forward into the next phase. It's always an interesting time in an Olympic cycle. You're not looking back any more but there is still opportunity to change, to hone it to where we want to be.\"</p><p>On the opening day, Great Britain will want to know the extent of their team sprinter Jess Varnish's recovery from the back injury that kept her out for many months after the London Games. However, the performance of the men's trio will be just as closely scrutinised after their fifth place last year in Minsk showed they are struggling to come to terms with the departure of the iconic Sir Chris Hoy, who will accompany GB in Cali as a mentor.</p><p>Great Britain have taken the last two Olympic titles in the men's team sprint but have not won a world championship since 2005, something that has left their senior figure, Jason Kenny, increasingly frustrated. \"We have not been going that slowly but everyone else seems to have made a step up and we have been left behind a little bit, so we have been chasing.</p><p>\"The Germans have made a real step forward and destroyed the world record – our world record – in Mexico and they destroyed us in Mexico along with it. They definitely seem to have picked their game up this year. The French have been consistently right at the top for years and years and then behind those two you have got us, the Australians, the Russians, all snapping at their heels. We have not got any particular weakness as such. It is not like we are losing all our time in the first half or the last half or the middle, we are just losing it all. All the way round we are haemorrhaging time – it is pretty depressing in that sense.\"</p><p>There is also speculation over the role of Brailsford, as the performance director concedes he is finding it \"more and more difficult\" to reconcile his twin roles of heading the Olympic programme and the Team Sky professional squad. There are rumours that he is likely to scale back his involvement with British Cycling – this will be the second track Worlds in a row he has opted to miss – and he concedes he will review his role after the championships.</p><p>\"The thing I am concerned about is to make sure the British cycling team is in the best possible shape it could be heading into Rio and that I feel that I'm contributing fully to make sure that happens. And that the appropriate structure is in place to make sure that happens. In other words, if I was occupying a space and for whatever reason I didn't feel I was optimising what I could do, then I would change my role so that someone could be maximising that particular part.\"</p><p>If Brailsford does indeed opt for Team Sky over GB when his team have left Colombia behind, the phrase '<em>après moi, le déluge</em>' will apply to rather more than the Cali thunderstorms.</p>","headline":"Great Britain look to weather Cali storms amid pre-Olympic speculation","trailText":"In the buildup to Rio and with other nations leading the way, speculation continues about the future of Dave Brailsford after the world track championships in Colombia","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2014/2/25/1393350617038/The-British-mens-team-spr-006.jpg","wordcount":"858","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-28T22:00:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/feb/25/great-britain-cali-olympic-rio-world-track-championships-colombia","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/sport/2014/feb/25/great-britain-cali-olympic-rio-world-track-championships-colombia","tags":[{"id":"sport/dave-brailsford","webTitle":"Dave Brailsford","type":"keyword","sectionId":"sport","sectionName":"Sport","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.co